 translators]]\n[[Category:Extra Ladies of the Order of the Garter]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Girton College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:House of Gl\u00fccksburg (Denmark)]]\n[[Category:House of Monpezat]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at North Foreland Lodge]]\n[[Category:Nobility from Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Reigning Protestant monarchs]]\n[[Category:Queens regnant]]\n[[Category:Tolkien artists]]\n[[Category:Translators to Danish]]\n<!-- Honours -->\n[[Category:Collars of the Order of Abdulaziz al Saud]]\n[[Category:Collars of the Order of the Aztec Eagle]]\n[[Category:Cordons of the Order of Stara Planina]]\n[[Category:Grand Collars of the Order of Prince Henry]]\n[[Category:Grand Collars of the Order of Saint James of the Sword]]\n[[Category:Grand Collars of the Order of the Southern Cross]]\n[[Category:Grand Commanders of the Order of the Dannebrog]]\n[[Category:Grand Cordons of the Order of Merit of the Republic of Poland]]\n[[Category:Grand Cordons of the Order of the Precious Crown]]\n[[Category:Grand Cordons of the Order of the Nile]]\n[[Category:Grand Cordons of the Order of the Star of Jordan]]\n[[Category:Grand Croix of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of Ouissam Alaouite]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of the Liberator General San Martin]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of the White Double Cross]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of Vytautas the Great]]\n[[Category:Honorary Dames Grand Cross of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross with Collar of the Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Golden Fleece]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Order of the Gold Lion of the House of Nassau]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Nersornaat]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Collar of the Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Grand Star of the Decoration for Services to the Republic of Austria]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Freedom of the Republic of Slovenia]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Royal Victorian Chain]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Pleiades (Iran)]]\n[[Category:20th-century women writers]]\n[[Category:Honorary Fellows of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses Special Class of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Society of Antiquaries of London]]\n[[Category:20th-century women rulers]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people||Margaret of Denmark (disambiguation)}}\n \n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name           = Margrethe II of Denmark\n| image          = Drottning Margrethe av Danmark.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Margrethe in May 2012\n| succession     = [[Queen of Denmark]]\n| reign          = 14 January 1972 \u2013 present\n| coronation     = \n| cor-type       = \n| predecessor    = [[Frederick IX of Denmark|Frederick IX]]\n| pre-type       = \n| successor      = [[Crown Prince Frederik|Frederik]]\n| suc-type       = Heir apparent\n| regent         = {{list collapsed|title=''See list''|1=\n{{List collapsed|title=''[[Prime Minister of Denmark|Denmark]]''|1=[[Jens Otto Krag]]<br />[[Anker J\u00f8rgensen]]<br />[[Poul Hartling]]<br />[[Poul Schl\u00fcter]]<br />[[Poul Nyrup Rasmussen]]<br />[[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]]<br />[[Lars L\u00f8kke Rasmussen]]<br />[[Helle Thorning-Schmidt]]<br />[[Lars L\u00f8kke Rasmussen]]<br />[[Mette Frederiksen]]}}\n{{List collapsed|title=''[[Prime Minister of the Faroe Islands|Faroe Islands]]''|1=[[Atli P. Dam|Atli Dam]]<br />[[J\u00f3gvan Sundstein]]<br />[[Marita Petersen]]<br />[[Edmund Joensen]]<br />[[Anfinn Kallsberg]]<br />[[J\u00f3annes Eidesgaard]]<br />[[Kaj Leo Johannesen]]<br />[[Aksel V. Johannesen]]<br />[[B\u00e1r\u00f0ur \u00e1 Steig Nielsen]]}}\n{{List collapsed|title=''[[Prime Minister of Greenland|Greenland]]''|1=[[Jonathan Motzfeldt]]<br />[[Lars Emil Johansen]]<br />[[Hans Enoksen]]<br />[[Kuupik Kleist]]<br />[[Aleqa Hammond]]<br />[[Kim Kielsen]]}}\n}}\n| reg-type       = {{nowrap|[[Prime Minister of Denmark|Prime Ministers]]}}\n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1940|4|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Amalienborg]], [[Copenhagen]], Denmark\n| spouse         = {{marriage|[[Henri de Laborde de Monpezat]]|10 June 1967|13 February 2018|end=d.}}\n| spouse-type    = Spouse\n| issue          = {{plain list|\n* [[Frederik, Crown Prince of Denmark]]\n* [[Prince Joachim of Denmark|Prince Joachim]]\n}}\n| issue-link     = #Family\n| full name      = Margrethe Alexandrine \u00de\u00f3rhildur Ingrid\n| house          = [[House of Gl\u00fccksburg|Gl\u00fccksburg]]<ref>{{cite web| title=150 years of the House of Gl\u00fccksborg| url=http://kongehuset.dk/english/Menu/news/150-years-of-the-house-of-glcksborg| accessdate=25 October 2014}}</ref>\n| father         = [[Frederick IX of Denmark]]\n| mother         = [[Ingrid of Sweden]]\n| signature      = Margrethe II - signature.svg\n|religion    = [[Church of Denmark]]\n}}\n{{Danish Royal Family}}\n'''Margrethe II''' ({{IPA-da|ma\u02c8k\u0281e\u02c0t\u0259|pron}}; full name: ''Margrethe Alexandrine \u00de\u00f3rhildur Ingrid''; born 16 April 1940) is [[Queen of Denmark]], as well as the supreme authority of the [[Church of Denmark]] and [[commander-in-chief]] of the [[Danish Defence]]. Born into the [[House of Gl\u00fccksburg]], a [[royal house]] with origins in [[northern Germany]], she was the eldest child of [[Frederick IX of Denmark]] and [[Ingrid of Sweden]]. She became [[heir presumptive]] to her father in 1953, when [[Danish Act of Succession|a constitutional amendment]] allowed women to inherit the throne.\n\nMargrethe succeeded her father upon his death on 14 January 1972. On her accession, she became the first female monarch of Denmark since [[Margaret I of Denmark|Margrethe I]], ruler of the [[Scandinavia]]n kingdoms in 1375\u20131412 during the [[Kalmar Union]]. In 1967, she married [[Henrik, Prince Consort of Denmark|Henri de Laborde de Monpezat]], with whom she had two sons: [[Crown Prince Frederik]] and [[Prince Joachim of Denmark|Prince Joachim]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Amalienborg cph.jpg|thumb|left|Princess Margrethe's birthplace: Frederik VIII's Palace at [[Amalienborg]], photographed in 2006]]\nPrincess Margrethe was born 16 April 1940 at [[Amalienborg]] in [[Copenhagen]] as the first child of the Crown Prince and Crown Princess (later [[King Frederick IX]] and [[Queen Ingrid]]). Her father was the eldest son of the then-reigning [[King Christian X]], while her mother was the only daughter of the Crown Prince of Sweden (later [[King Gustaf VI Adolf]]). Her birth took place just one week after [[Nazi Germany]]'s [[German invasion of Denmark (1940)|invasion of Denmark]] on 9 April 1940.<ref name=r1/>\n\nShe was [[baptism|baptised]] on 14 May in the [[Holmen Church]] in [[Copenhagen]].<ref name=r1/> The Princess's [[godparent]]s were: [[King Christian X]] (paternal grandfather); [[Prince Knud of Denmark|Hereditary Prince Knud]] (paternal uncle); [[Prince Axel of Denmark|Prince Axel]] (her paternal grandfather's first cousin); [[Gustaf V of Sweden|King Gustaf V of Sweden]] (maternal great-grandfather); [[Gustaf VI Adolf of Sweden|Crown Prince Gustaf Adolf of Sweden]] (maternal grandfather); [[Prince Gustaf Adolf, Duke of V\u00e4sterbotten]] (her maternal uncle); [[Prince Arthur, Duke of Connaught and Strathearn]] (maternal great-grandfather).\n\nShe was named Margrethe after her late maternal grandmother, [[Crown Princess Margaret of Sweden]], Alexandrine after her paternal grandmother, [[Alexandrine of Mecklenburg-Schwerin|Queen Alexandrine]], and Ingrid after her mother. Since her paternal grandfather was also the [[King of Iceland]], she was given the [[Icelandic language|Icelandic]] name \u00de\u00f3rhildur.<ref>{{cite web | title = Navnet til den ny prinsesse... | website = nfi.ku.dk | publisher = Nordisk Forskningsinstitut, [[University of Copenhagen]] | date = 18 May 2012 | url = http://nfi.ku.dk/nyheder/prinsessenavn2012/ | access-date = 23 January 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170202083411/http://nfi.ku.dk/nyheder/prinsessenavn2012/ | archive-date = 2 February 2017 | url-status=dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nWhen Margrethe was four years old, in 1944, her younger sister [[Princess Benedikte of Denmark|Princess Benedikte]] was born. Princess Benedikte later married [[Prince Richard of Sayn-Wittgenstein-Berleburg]] and lives some of the time in Germany. Her second sister, [[Queen Anne-Marie of Greece|Princess Anne-Marie]], was born in 1946. Anne-Marie later married [[Constantine II of Greece|Constantine II of the Hellenes]] and currently lives in [[Greece]].\n\nMargrethe and her sisters grew up in apartments at Frederick VIII's Palace at Amalienborg in Copenhagen and in [[Fredensborg Palace]] in [[North Zealand]]. She spent summer holidays with the royal family in her parent's summer residence at [[Gr\u00e5sten Palace]] in [[Southern Jutland]]. On 20 April 1947, King Christian X died and Margrethe's father ascended the throne as King Frederick IX.\n\n==Heir presumptive==\n[[File:Margrethe II of Denmark 1966.jpg|thumb|right|Princess Margrethe in 1966]]\nAt the time of her birth, only males could ascend the throne of Denmark, owing to the changes in succession laws enacted in the 1850s when the [[Schleswig-Holstein-Sonderburg-Gl\u00fccksburg|Gl\u00fccksburg]] branch was chosen to succeed. As she had no brothers, it was assumed that her uncle [[Knud, Hereditary Prince of Denmark|Prince Knud]] would one day assume the throne.\n\nThe process of changing the constitution started in 1947, not long after her father ascended the throne and it became clear that Queen Ingrid would have no more children. The popularity of Frederick and his daughters and the more prominent role of women in Danish life started the complicated process of altering the constitution. The law required that the proposal be passed by two successive Parliaments and then by a referendum, which occurred 27 March 1953. The new [[Danish Act of Succession|Act of Succession]] permitted female [[Order of succession|succession]] to the throne of Denmark, according to [[male-preference cognatic primogeniture]], where a female can ascend to the throne only if she does not have a brother. Princess Margrethe therefore became [[heir presumptive]].<ref name=r1/>\n\nOn her eighteenth birthday, 16 April 1958, Margrethe was given a seat in the [[Danish Council of State|Council of State]]. She subsequently chaired the meetings of the Council in the absence of the King.<ref name=r1/>\n\nIn 1960, together with the princesses of Sweden and Norway, she travelled to the United States, which included a visit to [[Los Angeles]], and to the [[Paramount Studios]], where they met several celebrities, including [[Dean Martin]], [[Jerry Lewis]] and [[Elvis Presley]].<ref name=Elvis>{{cite web|title=Elvis Presley with Princesses Margrethe of Denmark, Astrid of Norway, and Margaretha of Sweden|url=http://www.elvispresleymusic.com.au/pictures/1960_june_7.html#sthash.ORaSOwgy.dd9JxPDB.dpbs|website=Elvispresleymusic.com.au|date=7 June 1960|accessdate=11 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909182159/http://www.elvispresleymusic.com.au/pictures/1960_june_7.html#sthash.ORaSOwgy.dd9JxPDB.dpbs|archivedate=9 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nMargrethe was educated at the private school [[N. Zahle's School]] in Copenhagen from which she graduated in 1959. She spent a year at [[North Foreland Lodge]], a [[boarding school]] for girls in [[Hampshire]], England,<ref name=ILN>{{cite news|work=The Illustrated London News|volume=227|issue=2 |year=1955|page=552|title=Princess Margrethe, who is fifteen and is heir presumptive to the Danish throne, is to study for a year in England at North Foreland Lodge, a girls' boarding school near Basingstoke, in Hampshire...}}</ref> and later studied [[prehistoric]] [[archaeology]] at [[Girton College, Cambridge]], during 1960\u20131961, [[political science]] at [[Aarhus University]] between 1961 and 1962, attended the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]] in 1963, and was at the [[London School of Economics]] in 1965.<ref name=\"Margrethe and Henrik Biography\"/> She is a [[Fellow]] of the [[Society of Antiquaries of London]].<ref name=r1/>\n\nQueen Margrethe is fluent in [[Danish language|Danish]], French, English, [[Swedish language|Swedish]] and German, and has a limited knowledge of [[Faroese language|Faroese]].<ref name=r1/><ref name=\"Margrethe and Henrik Biography\"/>\n\n===Marriage and children===\n[[File:Royal Wedding Stockholm 2010-Konserthuset-421.jpg|left|thumb|Queen Margrethe II and her consort, Prince Henrik, in 2010.]]\nPrincess Margrethe married a French diplomat, [[Henrik, Prince Consort of Denmark|Henri de Laborde de Monpezat]], 10 June 1967, at the [[Holmen Church]] in [[Copenhagen]]. Laborde de Monpezat received the style and title of \"His Royal Highness Prince Henrik of Denmark\" because of his new position as the spouse of the heir presumptive to the Danish [[throne]].<ref name=r1/> They were married for over fifty years, until his death on 13 February 2018.\n\nMargrethe gave birth to her first child 26 May 1968. By tradition, Danish kings were alternately named either Frederick or Christian. She chose to maintain this by assuming the position of a Christian, and thus named her eldest son [[Frederik, Crown Prince of Denmark|Frederik]]. A second child, named [[Prince Joachim of Denmark|Joachim]], was born 7 June 1969.<ref name=r1/>\n\n==Reign==\n[[File:Faroe stamp 302 Queen Margrethe.jpg|thumb|200px|Margrethe II of Denmark in a costume of the [[Faroese people]]. Stamp FR 302 of [[Postverk F\u00f8roya]], [[Faroe Islands]], issued 14 January 1997.]]\n\n===Succession===\nShortly after [[Frederick IX of Denmark|King Frederick IX]] delivered his New Year's Address to the Nation at the 1971/72 turn of the year, he fell ill. At his death 14 days later, 14 January 1972, Margrethe succeeded to the throne at the age of 31, becoming the first female Danish [[monarch|sovereign]] under the new Act of Succession. She was proclaimed Queen from the balcony of [[Christiansborg Palace]] 15 January 1972, by [[Prime Minister of Denmark|Prime Minister]] [[Jens Otto Krag]]. Queen Margrethe II relinquished all the monarch's former titles except the title to Denmark, hence her style \"[[By the Grace of God]], Queen of Denmark\" ({{lang-da|Margrethe den Anden, af Guds N\u00e5de Danmarks Dronning}}). The Queen chose the [[Royal mottos of Danish monarchs|motto]]: ''God's help, the love of The People, Denmark's strength.''<ref name=\"Margrethe and Henrik Biography\"/>\n\nIn her first address to the people, Queen Margrethe II said: {{quote|My beloved father, our King, is dead. The task that my father had carried for nearly 25 years is now resting on my shoulders. I pray to God to give me help and strength to carry the heavy heritage. May the trust that was given to my father also be granted to me.<ref name=\"radical royalist\">{{cite journal|url=http://radicalroyalist.blogspot.com.br/2012_01_01_archive.html#post-body-3282259268133616607|publisher=Radical Royalist|title=Queen Margrethe II of Denmark 40 years on the Throne|date=13 January 2012|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref>}}\n\n===Constitutional role===\nThe Queen's main tasks are to represent the Kingdom abroad and to be a unifying figure at home. The Queen performs the latter task by accepting invitations to open exhibitions, attending anniversaries, inaugurating bridges, etc. She receives foreign ambassadors and awards honours and medals. \n\nAs an unelected public official, the Queen takes no part in party politics and does not express any political opinions. Although she has the right to vote, she opts not to do so to avoid even the appearance of partisanship.<ref name=r1/>\n\nAfter an election where the incumbent [[Prime Minister of Denmark|Prime Minister]] does not have a majority behind him or her, the Queen holds a \u201cDronningerunde\u201d (Queen's meeting) in which she meets the chairmen of each of the [[List of political parties in Denmark|Danish political parties]].<ref name=Todays>{{cite web |url=http://kongehuset.dk/english/the-monarchy-in-denmark/the-monarchy-today |title=The Monarchy today |publisher=Kongehuset.dk |accessdate=11 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215082552/http://kongehuset.dk/english/the-monarchy-in-denmark/the-monarchy-today |archive-date=15 February 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nEach party has the choice of selecting a Royal Investigator to lead these negotiations or alternatively, give the incumbent Prime Minister the mandate to continue his government as is. In theory each party could choose its own leader as Royal Investigator, the social liberal [[Det Radikale Venstre]] did so in 2006, but often only one Royal Investigator is chosen plus the Prime Minister, before each election. The leader who, at that meeting succeeds in securing a majority of the seats in the [[Folketing]], is by royal decree charged with the task of forming a new government. (It has never happened in more modern history{{when|date=January 2020}} that any party has held a majority on its own.)\n\nOnce the government has been formed, it is formally appointed by the Queen. Officially, it is the Queen who is the head of government, and she therefore presides over the Council of State ([[privy council]]), where the acts of legislation which have been passed by the parliament are signed into law. In practice, however, nearly all of the Queen's formal powers are exercised by the [[Cabinet of Denmark]].\n\nIn addition to her roles in her own country, the Queen is also the [[Colonel-in-Chief]] of the [[Princess of Wales's Royal Regiment|Princess of Wales's Royal Regiment (Queen's and Royal Hampshires)]], an infantry regiment of the [[British Army]], following a tradition in her family.<ref name=r1/>\n\n===Ruby Jubilee===\nQueen Margrethe II celebrated her [[Ruby Jubilee]], the 40th year on the throne, on 14 January 2012.<ref name=BBC40>{{cite news |title=Queen Margrethe II of Denmark marks 40 years on the throne |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16531823 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=12 January 2012}}</ref> This was marked by a carriage procession, a gala banquet at [[Christiansborg Palace]] and numerous TV interviews.\n\n=== Immigration debate ===\nIn an interview within the 2016 book ''De dybeste r\u00f8dder'' (''The Deepest Roots''), according to historians at the [[South Campus (University of Copenhagen)|Saxo Institute]] of the [[University of Copenhagen]] she showed a change in attitude to immigration towards a more restrictive stance. She stated that the Danish people should have more explicitly clarified the rules and values of Danish culture in order to be able to teach them to new arrivals. She further stated that the Danes in general have underestimated the difficulties involved in successful integration of immigrants, exemplified with the rules of a democracy not being clarified to Muslim immigrants and a lack of readiness to enforce those rules. This was received as a change in line with the attitude of the Danish people.<ref name=\"tv2_dk_23October2016\">{{cite news|title=Historiker om Margrethes danskheds-udtalelse: - Hun har fulgt folkesj\u00e6lens bekymringer|url=http://nyheder.tv2.dk/politik/2016-10-23-historiker-om-margrethes-danskheds-udtalelse-hun-har-fulgt-folkesjaelens|accessdate=25 October 2016|publisher=[[TV2 (Denmark)]]|date=23 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"b_dk_22October2016\">{{cite news|title=Dronning Margrethe om integration: \"Det er ikke en naturlov, at man bliver dansker af at bo i Danmark\"|url=http://www.b.dk/politiko/dronning-margrethe-om-integration-det-er-ikke-en-naturlov-at-man-bliver-dans|accessdate=25 October 2016|newspaper=[[Berlingske Tidende]]|date=22 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and interests==\n\nThe official residences of the Queen are [[Amalienborg Palace]] in Copenhagen and [[Fredensborg Palace]]. Her summer residence is [[Gr\u00e5sten Palace]] near [[S\u00f8nderborg]], the former home of her mother, Queen Ingrid, who died in 2000.\n\nMargrethe is an accomplished [[Painting|painter]], and has held many art shows over the years. Her illustrations\u2014under the pseudonym Ingahild Grathmer\u2014were used for Danish editions of ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'', which she was encouraged to illustrate in the early 1970s. She sent them to [[J. R. R. Tolkien]] who was struck by the similarity of her drawings to his own style. Margrethe's drawings were redrawn by the British artist [[Eric Fraser (illustrator)|Eric Fraser]] in the translation published in 1977 and re-issued in 2002. In 2000, she illustrated Henrik, the Prince Consort's [[Cantabile (book)|poetry collection ''Cantabile'']]. She is also an accomplished [[Translation|translator]] and is said to have participated in the Danish translation of ''The Lord of the Rings''.<ref name=\"Margrethe and Henrik Biography\">{{cite web|url=http://www.royalinsight.net/content/margrethe-henrik-biography |title=Margrethe and Henrik Biography |publisher=Royalinsight.net |date=16 April 1940 |accessdate=3 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111030181923/http://www.royalinsight.net/content/margrethe-henrik-biography |archivedate=30 October 2011 }}</ref>  Another skill she possesses is costume designing, having designed the costumes for the [[Royal Danish Ballet]]'s production of ''[[A Folk Tale]]'' and for the 2009 [[Peter Flinth]] film, ''De vilde svaner'' (''The Wild Swans'').<ref name=r1>{{cite web|url=http://kongehuset.dk/english/the-royal-house/Regentparret/hm-the-queen|publisher=Kongehuset.dk| title=Her Majesty Queen Margrethe II|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=Imdb>{{cite web| url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1499643/|title=De vilde svaner (2009)| website=[[Internet Movie Database]]| accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> She also designs her own clothes and is known for her colourful and sometimes eccentric clothing choices. Margrethe also wears designs by former [[Pierre Balmain]] designer Erik Mortensen, [[J\u00f8rgen Bender]], and Birgitte Taulow.<ref name=Style>{{cite journal|url=http://orderofsplendor.blogspot.com/2012/01/flashback-friday-queen-margrethes-style.html|publisher=The Royal Order of Sartorial Splendor|title=Flashback Friday: Queen Margrethe's Styl|date=13 January 2012|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' in March 2013 listed her as one of the fifty best-dressed over 50s.<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|title=The 50 best-dressed over 50s |url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/gallery/2013/mar/29/50-best-dressed-over-50s|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|location=[[Manchester]]|first1=Jess |last1=Cartner-Morley|first2=Helen|last2=Mirren|first3=Arianna|last3=Huffington|first4=Valerie|last4=Amos|date=28 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nMargrethe is a [[Chain smoking|chain smoker]], and she is famous for her [[tobacco]] habit.<ref name=cancer>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/1235946.stm|title=Danish royals angry at cancer accusation|work=BBC News|date=23 March 2001 |first=Julian|last=Isherwood|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> However, on 23 November 2006, the Danish newspaper'' B.T.'' reported an announcement from the Royal Court stating that in the future the Queen would smoke only in private.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bt.dk/article/20061123/ROYALT/111230530/1058 |title=Margrethe skruer ned for r\u00f8gen |accessdate=7 May 2014 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071016113125/http://www.bt.dk/article/20061123/ROYALT/111230530/1058 |archivedate=16 October 2007}}. bt.dk. 26 November 2006</ref>\n\nA statement in a 2005 authorized biography about the Queen (entitled ''Margrethe'') focused on her views of Islam: \"We are being challenged by Islam these years. Globally as well as locally. There is something impressive about people for whom religion imbues their existence, from dusk to dawn, from cradle to grave. There are also Christians who feel this way. There is something endearing about people who give themselves up completely to their faith. But there is likewise something frightening about such a totality, which also is a feature of Islam. A counterbalance has to be found, and one has to, at times, run the risk of having unflattering labels placed on you. For there are some things for which one should display no tolerance. And when we are tolerant, we must know whether it is because of convenience or conviction.\"<ref name=Cleaver>{{cite news| title=We need a counter-balance to Islam, says Danish queen| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/denmark/1487909/We-need-a-counter-balance-to-Islam-says-Danish-queen.html|location=London|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|first=Hannah|last=Cleaver|date=15 April 2005|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\n{{main|Danish Royal Family}}\n[[File:Monarchy Of Denmark April 2010.jpg|thumb|The Queen surrounded by her family waving to crowds on her 70th birthday in April 2010. From left to right: [[Mary, Crown Princess of Denmark|the Crown Princess]], [[Prince Felix of Denmark|Prince Felix]], [[Frederik, Crown Prince of Denmark|the Crown Prince]], [[Prince Christian of Denmark|Prince Christian]], the Queen, [[Prince Nikolai of Denmark|Prince Nikolai]], [[Henrik, Prince Consort of Denmark|Prince Consort Henrik]], [[Prince Joachim of Denmark|Prince Joachim]] and [[Princess Isabella of Denmark|Princess Isabella]]]]\nThe Queen has two children and eight grandchildren, all born at Rigshospitalet in Copenhagen:\n\n*[[Frederik, Crown Prince of Denmark|Crown Prince Frederik]] (born 26 May 1968). He was married to [[Mary Donaldson]] on 14 May 2004 at [[Copenhagen Cathedral]], Copenhagen. The couple have four children:\n**[[Prince Christian of Denmark|Prince Christian]] (born 15 October 2005)\n**[[Princess Isabella of Denmark|Princess Isabella]] (born 21 April 2007)\n**[[Prince Vincent of Denmark|Prince Vincent]] (born 8 January 2011)\n**[[Princess Josephine of Denmark|Princess Josephine]] (born 8 January 2011)\n*[[Prince Joachim of Denmark|Prince Joachim]] (born 7 June 1969). He was married to [[Alexandra Manley]] on 18 November 1995 at [[Frederiksborg Palace|Frederiksborg Palace Church]], [[Hiller\u00f8d]]. They divorced on 8 April 2005. He was married secondly to [[Marie Cavallier]] on 24 May 2008 at M\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder Church, M\u00f8gelt\u00f8nder. Joachim has four children, three sons and one daughter:\n**[[Prince Nikolai of Denmark|Prince Nikolai]] (born 28 August 1999)\n**[[Prince Felix of Denmark|Prince Felix]] (born 22 July 2002)\n**[[Prince Henrik of Denmark (born 2009)|Prince Henrik]] (born 4 May 2009)\n**[[Princess Athena of Denmark|Princess Athena]] (born 24 January 2012)\n\nIn 2008, the Queen announced that her male-line descendants would bear the additional title of Count or Countess of Monpezat, in recognition of her husband's ancestry.<ref name=monpezat>{{cite web|title=Monpezat til Frederik og Joachim|trans-title=Monpezat for Frederik and Joachim|work=[[Berlingske|Berlingske Tidende]]|date=30 April 2008|url=http://www.berlingske.dk/article/20080430/danmark/804300370/|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Queen Margrethe 21-06-2005 V\u00e1gur.jpg|thumb|right|Queen Margrethe II in [[V\u00e1gur]], [[Faroe Islands]], 21 June 2005]]\n[[File:Queen Margrethe II and Prince Henrik of Denmark welcome George W. Bush and Laura Bush.jpg|thumb|Queen Margrethe II and her husband the Prince Consort welcome President [[George W. Bush]] and his wife [[Laura Bush]] at [[Fredensborg Palace]], 5 July 2005.]]\n[[File:Margrethe II Brazilian President.jpg|thumb|Margrethe II with Brazilian President [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]] during the latter's visit to Denmark, 12 September 2007.]]\n\n==Honours==\nShe is the 1,188th [[knight]] of the [[Order of the Golden Fleece]] in Spain, and only the 7th Lady of the [[Order of the Garter]] since 1901, when [[Edward VII]] appointed his consort a member. She is also [[Colonel-in-Chief]] of [[The Princess of Wales's Royal Regiment (Queen's and Royal Hampshires)]] in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=54745 |date=21 April 1997|page=4766 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\n[[Queen Margrethe II Land]] in Northeast [[Greenland]] was named in her honour on 16 April 1990 on the occasion of her 50th birthday.<ref name=\"cat\">{{cite book|chapter=Catalogue of place names in northern East Greenland | title=Exploration history and place names of northern East Greenland |last=Higgins|first=Anthony K. |year=2010 |publisher=Geological Survey of Denmark and Greenland |chapter-url=http://www.eng.geus.dk/media/12136/nr21_p001-368.pdf |accessdate=22 August 2019 |page=158 }}</ref>\n\n{{See also|List of honours of the Danish Royal Family by country}}\n\n===National===\n* {{flag|Denmark}}: Recipient of the [[Dannebrogordenens H\u00e6derstegn|Cross of Honour of the Order of the Dannebrog]] ('''D.Ht.''')<ref name=\"QueenMargretheOrdersPage\">{{cite web|website=Kongehuset.dk|url=http://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=fr&nv=1&rurl=translate.google.be&sl=auto&tl=en&u=http://kongehuset.dk/den-kongelige-familie/regentparret/hm-dronningen%3Fqt-view__node_revision__panel_pane_4%3D1&usg=ALkJrhiawHe9kVNevR1HE9jKFJNEXCIW_Q#qt-view__node_revision__panel_pane_4|title=Page with Margrethes national honours|accessdate=16 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"OrderInsignia\">{{cite web|website=Zimbio.com|url=http://www1.pictures.zimbio.com/gi/Queen+Margrethe+II+Queen+Margrethe+II+Denmark+6YLHf85aad_l.jpg |format=JPG|title=Margrethe wearing national honours|accessdate=16 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"OrderInsignia1\">{{cite web|website=Zimbio.com|url=http://www2.pictures.zimbio.com/gi/Queen+Margrethe+II+Queen+Margrethe+II+Denmark+x46OObtluk8l.jpg|format=JPG|title=Margrethe wearing national orders|accessdate=16 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"GrandCollarSet\">{{cite web|website=Xinhuanet.com|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/photo/2010-09/02/13475043_31n.jpg|format=JPG|title=Margrethe wearing order of the elephant and other honours|accessdate=16 March 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302043641/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/photo/2010-09/02/13475043_31n.jpg|archivedate=2 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"DanishAndSwedishOrders\">{{cite web|website=Mylusciouslife.com|url=http://www.mylusciouslife.com/wp-content/uploads/galleries/post-15194/Crowns%20for%20a%20queen%20-%20queen%20margarethe%20wearing%20royal%20tiara.jpg|format=JPG|title=Margrethe wearing Danish and Swedish Orders insignia|accessdate=16 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"MiniInsignia\">{{cite web|website=Blogger.com|url=https://royaltyaroundtheworld.files.wordpress.com/2014/04/emeraldsmarg.jpg|format=JPG|title=Margrethe wearing the Royal family order and Dannebrog cross|accessdate=16 March 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312053631/https://royaltyaroundtheworld.files.wordpress.com/2014/04/emeraldsmarg.jpg|archivedate=12 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Denmark}}: Recipient of the [[Long Service Awards (Denmark)|Air Force Long Service Medal]]<ref name=\"QueenMargretheOrdersPage\" />\n* {{flag|Denmark}}: Recipient of the [[List of orders, decorations, and medals of the Kingdom of Denmark#Royally Approved Orders and Medals|Homeguard Medal of Merit]]<ref name=\"QueenMargretheOrdersPage\" />\n* {{flag|Denmark}}: Recipient of the [[Long Service Awards (Denmark)|25 years of Homeguard Service Medal]]<ref name=\"QueenMargretheOrdersPage\" />\n* {{flag|Denmark}}: Recipient of the [[Badge of Honor of the League of Civil Defense|Medal of Honour of the League of Civil Defence]]<ref name=\"QueenMargretheOrdersPage\" />\n* {{flag|Denmark}}: Recipi